item.title: Which tracks should Auxy repost? (Don't recommend your own releases/collabs!)
item.dc:creator: ThoughtfulNoise
item.description:
As someone who previously worked at SC, you‚Äôre possibly as well placed as anyone here to speak on the supposed value of the SC repost feature.

I tend to repost only those tracks which I think might appeal to people who enjoy what I‚Äôm putting out.

There‚Äôs an unspoken mutuality about reposting, where reposting others might be reciprocated behaviour that can expand audience reach beyond your existing followers.

The difference with SC is that there‚Äôs no clear line between pure listeners and uploaders/producers. Listeners have better places to go, so SC likely skews disproportionately towards producers compared to other music platforms. So, any use of repost is likely being impacted by that skew.

 

As for the Auxy crowd‚Ä¶ I suspect the Auxy user base skews extremely towards hobbyists, rather than aspiring pros, so aren‚Äôt optimising their SC profiles for audience building. Being quite young on average, perhaps the social aspects are also influencing repost popularity (i.e. a generation who grew up with online social media).

Tbf, Auxy itself might be part of a feedback loop in that hobbyist skew ‚Äî though it‚Äôs likely also a symptom of the mobile music production space.

 

I‚Äôd be curious to know what % of Auxy people who post on SC also publish on Spotify, etc‚Ä¶ as, I suspect, that‚Äôs generally another signifier that they‚Äôre taking their music a bit more seriously.

item.dc:creator: Auxy
item.description:
Can you explain why most people who upload tracks to SoundCloud, also frequently repost tracks from other artists? Makes it really hard to keep track of what people upload just by following, since the tracks you make yourselves are drowning in the stream of other tracks. I think it makes sense to repost stuff if you want to be a curator of things, but I don‚Äôt see why it makes sense for people trying to build their own profiles on SoudCloud.
